for poor sailors, tossed by stormy seas; for the oppressed millions-61-groaning 
under the heel of European monarchies and Oriental despotisms; for such as have 
the light and the good tidings, and yet have not eyes to see nor ears to hear wi
thal; for the heathen in the far islands of the sea; and closed with a supplicat
ion that the words he was about to speak might find grace and favor, and be as s
eed sown in fertile ground, yielding in time a grateful harvest of good. Amen.Th
ere was a rustling of dresses, and the standing congregation sat down. The boy w
hose history this book relates did not enjoy the prayer, he only endured it -- i
